11 An Act relating to the workforce; directing the
Department of Human Services to develop pilot
12 program; describing financial eligibility; requiring
statewide implementation condition of successful
13 completion of the program; requiring annual reports;
providing for codification; and providing an
14 effective date.
15
16
17 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
18 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
19 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 28.4 of Title 56, unless there
20 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
21 A. The Legislature finds and declares that a Tri-Share
22 Workforce Pilot Program which allows participating employers,
23 employees, and the state to share equal responsibility for child
24 care of dependent children from birth to eight (8) years of age by
HB4199 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 the state matching the employer's contribution each up to one-third
2 (1/3) of the total cost with the parent paying the remaining cost,
3 to assist parents and caretakers to participate in the workforce.
4 B. The Department of Human Services shall develop and implement
5 a three-year Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program during the fiscal
6 year beginning July 1, 2026, testing the feasibility of
7 participating employers and the access to employees to high-quality,
8 affordable child care. The Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program shall
9 consist of two urban and four rural counties. The Department shall
10 select counties based on interest in employer participation and key
11 industry workforce needs.
12 C. Eligibility for the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program shall
13 consist of employees of participating employers whose household
14 income is between one hundred fifty percent (150%) and two hundred
15 fifty percent (250%) of the federal poverty level and who are not
16 eligible for child care subsidy.
17 D. The Department of Human Services shall establish guidelines
18 to implement the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program, and technical
19 assistance shall be included in the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot
20 Program. The Department of Human Services may contract with
21 existing training programs or other qualified providers with
22 experience relevant to Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program
23 participants for such technical assistance.
24
HB4199 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 E. Upon completion of the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program, if
2 it is determined that the project was effective in achieving the
3 objective of assisting employees with improving the stability,
4 affordability, access, and quality of child care, the Department of
5 Human Services shall implement a similar statewide program for
6 participating employers and qualified employees.
7 F. The Department of Human Services shall report to the
8 Legislature each year on the participation of employers and
9 employees, the availability of child care facilities, the costs of
10 child care facilities, and, to the extent practicable, the impact
11 the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program has had on the community in
12 assisting parents and caretakers to participate in the workforce or
13 access training that can advance their degrees. Following
14 successful completion of the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program,
15 effectiveness of the Tri-Share Workforce Pilot Program shall be
16 evaluated by the Department of Human Services in consultation with
17 the Oklahoma Incentive Evaluation Commission.
18 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
19
